
[1]mortmain

   MORT'MAIN, n. In law, possession of lands or tenements in dead hands,
   or hands that cannot alienate. Alienation in mortmain is an alienation
   of lands or tenements to any corporation, sole or aggregate,
   ecclesiastical or temporal, particularly to religious houses, by which
   the estate becomes perpetually inherent in the corporation and
   unalienable.
